<span class="quote">&gt; &gt; +                                * copy_one_pte() for explanation.</span>
<span class="quote">&gt; &gt; +                                */</span>
<span class="quote">&gt; &gt; +                               make_device_entry_read(&amp;entry);</span>
<span class="quote">&gt; &gt; +                               newpte = swp_entry_to_pte(entry);</span>
<span class="quote">&gt; &gt; +                               set_pte_at(mm, addr, pte, newpte);</span>
<span class="quote">&gt; &gt; +</span>
<span class="quote">&gt; &gt; +                               pages++;</span>
<span class="quote">&gt; &gt; +                       }</span>
<span class="quote">&gt; &gt;                 }</span>
<span class="quote">&gt; &gt;         } while (pte++, addr += PAGE_SIZE, addr != end);</span>
<span class="quote">&gt; &gt;         arch_leave_lazy_mmu_mode();</span>
<span class="quote">&gt; </span>
<span class="quote">&gt; I think this is a good example of how the usage of the generic</span>
<span class="quote">&gt; &quot;device&quot; term makes the new &quot;private&quot; code paths harder to spot /</span>
<span class="quote">&gt; discern from the current &quot;public&quot; requirements.</span>

I will change to devpriv

Thank for reviewing.

Cheers,
Jérôme
</pre>
